# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: dead-centre-engineering
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:dead-centre-engineering/air-cooled-engine] Air-cooled engines are widely seen in applications where weight or simplicity is the primary goal.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/air-cooled-engine] Their simplicity makes them suited for uses in small applications like chainsaws and lawn mowers, as well as small generators and similar roles.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/air-cooled-engine] These qualities also make them highly suitable for aviation use, where they are widely used in general aviation aircraft and as auxiliary power units on larger aircraft.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/air-cooled-engine] Their simplicity, in particular, also makes them common on motorcycles.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/air-cooled-engine] Most modern internal combustion engines are cooled by a closed circuit carrying liquid coolant through channels in the engine block and cylinder head.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/air-cooled-engine] A fluid in these channels absorbs heat and then flows to a heat exchanger or radiator where the coolant releases heat into the air (or raw water, in the case of marine engines).
[src:dead-centre-engineering/air-cooled-engine] Thus, while they are not *ultimately* cooled by the liquid, as the heat is exchanged with some other fluid like air, because of the liquid-coolant circuit they are known as *liquid-cooled*.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/air-cooled-engine] In contrast, heat generated by an air-cooled engine is released directly into the air.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/air-cooled-engine] Typically this is facilitated with metal fins covering the outside of the cylinder head and cylinders which increase the surface area that air can act on.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/air-cooled-engine] Air may be force fed with the use of a fan and shroud to achieve efficient cooling with high volumes of air or simply by natural air flow with well designed and angled fins.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/air-cooled-engine] In all combustion engines, a great percentage of the heat generated, around 44%, escapes through the exhaust.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/air-cooled-engine] Another 8% or so ends up in the oil, which itself has to be cooled in an oil cooler.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/air-cooled-engine] This means less than half of the heat has to be removed through other systems.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/air-cooled-engine] In an air-cooled engine, only about 12% of the heat flows out through the metal fins.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/air-cooled-engine] Air cooled engines usually run noisier, however it provides more simplicity which gives benefits when it comes to servicing and part replacement and is usually cheaper to be maintained.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/air-cooled-engine] Many motorcycles use air cooling for the sake of reducing weight and complexity.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/air-cooled-engine] Few current production automobiles have air-cooled engines (such as Tatra 815), but historically it was common for many high-volume vehicles.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/air-cooled-engine] The orientation of the engine cylinders is commonly found in either single-cylinder or coupled in groups of two, and cylinders are commonly oriented in a horizontal fashion as a flat engine, while vertical straight-four engine have been used.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/air-cooled-engine] During the 1920s and 30s there was a great debate in the aviation industry about the merits of air-cooled vs. liquid-cooled designs.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/air-cooled-engine] At the beginning of this period, the liquid used for cooling was water at ambient pressure.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/air-cooled-engine] The amount of heat carried away by a fluid is a function of its capacity and the difference in input and output temperatures.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/air-cooled-engine] As the boiling point of water is reduced with lower pressure, and the water could not be efficiently pumped as steam, radiators had to have enough cooling power to account for the loss in cooling power as the aircraft climbed.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/air-cooled-engine] The resulting radiators were quite large and caused a significant amount of aerodynamic drag.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/air-cooled-engine] This placed the two designs roughly equal in terms of power to drag, but the air-cooled designs were almost always lighter and simpler.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/air-cooled-engine] In 1921, the US Navy, largely due to the efforts of Commander Bruce G.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/air-cooled-engine] Leighton, decided that the simplicity of the air-cooled design would result in less maintenance workload, which was paramount given the limited working area of aircraft carriers.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/air-cooled-engine] Leighton's efforts led to the Navy underwriting air-cooled engine development at Pratt & Whitney and Wright Aeronautical.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/air-cooled-engine] Most other groups, especially in Europe where aircraft performance was rapidly improving, were more concerned with the issue of drag.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/air-cooled-engine] While air-cooled designs were common on light aircraft and trainers, as well as some transport aircraft and bombers, liquid-cooled designs remained much more common for fighters and high-performance bombers.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/air-cooled-engine] The drag issue was upset by the 1929 introduction of the NACA cowl, which greatly reduced the drag of air-cooled engines in spite of their larger frontal area, and the drag related to cooling was at this point largely even.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/air-cooled-engine] This also led to development work attempting to eliminate the radiator entirely using evaporative cooling, allowing it to turn to steam and running the steam through tubes located just under the skin of the wings and fuselage, where the fast moving outside air condensed it back to water.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/air-cooled-engine] While this concept was used on a number of record-setting aircraft in the late 1930s, it always proved impractical for production aircraft for a wide variety of reasons.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/air-cooled-engine] In 1929, Curtiss began experiments replacing water with ethylene glycol in a Curtiss D-12 engine.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/air-cooled-engine] Ethylene glycol could run up to 250°C and reduced the radiator size by 50% compared to water-cooled designs.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/air-cooled-engine] The experiments were extremely successful and by 1932 the company had switched all future designs to this coolant.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/air-cooled-engine] At the time, Union Carbide held a monopoly on the industrial process to make ethylene glycol, so it was initially used only in the US, with Allison Engines picking it up soon after.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/air-cooled-engine] It was not until the mid-1930s that Rolls-Royce adopted it as supplies improved, converting all of their engines to ethylene glycol.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/air-cooled-engine] With the much smaller radiators and less fluid in the system, the weight and drag of these designs was well below contemporary air-cooled designs.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/air-cooled-engine] On a weight basis, these liquid-cooled designs offered as much as 30% better performance.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/air-cooled-engine] In the late- and post-war era, the high-performance field quickly moved to jet engines.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/air-cooled-engine] This took away the primary market for late-model liquid-cooled engines.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/air-cooled-engine] Those roles that remained with piston power were mostly slower designs and civilian aircraft.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/air-cooled-engine] In these roles, the simplicity and reduction in servicing needs is far more important than drag, and from the end of the war on almost all piston aviation engines have been air-cooled, with few exceptions.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/air-cooled-engine] As of 2020, most of the engines manufactured by Lycoming and Continental are used by major manufacturers of light aircraft Cirrus, Cessna and so on.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/air-cooled-engine] Other engine manufactures using air-cooled engine technology are ULPower and Jabiru, more active in the Light-Sport Aircraft (LSA) and ultralight aircraft market.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/air-cooled-engine] Rotax uses a combination of air-cooled cylinders and liquid-cooled cylinder heads.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/air-cooled-engine] Some small diesel engines, e.g. those made by Deutz AG and Lister Petter are air-cooled.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/air-cooled-engine] Probably the only big Euro 5 truck air-cooled engine (V8 320 kW power 2100 N·m torque one) is being produced by Tatra.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/air-cooled-engine] BOMAG part of the FAYAT group also utilizes an air cooled inline 6 cylinder motor, in many of their construction vehicles.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/air-cooled-engine] Stationary or portable engines were commercially introduced early in the 1900s.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/air-cooled-engine] The first commercial production was by the New Way Motor Company of Lansing, Michigan, US.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/air-cooled-engine] The company produced air-cooled engines in single and twin cylinders in both horizontal and vertical cylinder format.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/air-cooled-engine] Subsequent to their initial production which was exported worldwide, other companies took up the advantages of this cooling method, especially in small portable engines.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/air-cooled-engine] Applications include mowers, generators, outboard motors, pump sets, saw benches and auxiliary power plants and more.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/air-cooling] In all cases, the air has to be cooler than the object or surface from which it is expected to remove heat.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/air-cooling] This is due to the second law of thermodynamics, which states that heat will only move spontaneously from a hot reservoir (the heat sink) to a cold reservoir (the air).
[src:dead-centre-engineering/air-cooling] When operating in an environment with lower air pressure like high altitude or airplane cabins, the cooling capacity has to be derated compared to that of sea level.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/air-cooling] A rule-of-thumb formula to note: 1 – (h/17500) = derating factor.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/air-cooling] Where *h* is the height over sea level in meters.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/air-cooling] And the result is the factor that should be multiplied with the cooling capacity in [W] to get the cooling capacity at the specified height over sea level.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/air-filter] A particulate **air filter** is a device composed of fibrous or porous materials which removes particulates such as smoke, dust, pollen, mold, viruses, and bacteria from the air.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/air-filter] Filters containing an adsorbent or catalyst such as charcoal (carbon) or baking sodamay also remove odors and gaseous pollutants, such as volatile organic compounds or ozone.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/air-filter] Air filters are typically constructed of foam, pleated paper, cotton, or spun fiberglass.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/air-filter] Oil bath air filters have fallen out of favour aside from niche uses.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/air-filter] Air ionizers use a different method, static electric charge, than air filters to attract and remove dust particles but they may also be supplemented with an air filter.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/air-filter] High efficiency particulate arrester (HEPA), originally called high-efficiency particulate absorber but also sometimes called high-efficiency particulate arresting or high-efficiency particulate arrestance, is a type of air filter.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/air-filter] Filters meeting the HEPA standard have many applications, including use in clean rooms for IC fabrication, medical facilities, automobiles, aircraft and homes.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/air-filter] The filter must satisfy certain standards of efficiency such as those set by the United States Department of Energy (DOE).
[src:dead-centre-engineering/air-filter] Varying standards define what qualifies as a HEPA filter.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/air-filter] The two most common standards EN 1822 and ASME AG-1 require an air filter must remove (from the air that passes through) 99.95% (European Standard) or 99.97% (ASME standard) of particles that have a size greater than or equal to 0.3 μm.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/air-filter] The cabin air filter, also known in the United Kingdom as a pollen filter, is typically a pleated filter that is placed in the outside-air intake for the vehicle's passenger compartment.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/air-filter] Some of these filters are rectangular, while others are uniquely shaped to fit the available space of particular vehicles' outside-air intakes.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/air-filter] The first automaker to include a disposable filter to keep the ventilation system clean was the Nash Motors "Weather Eye", introduced in 1940.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/air-filter] A reusable heater core filter was available as an optional accessory on Studebaker models beginning in 1959, including Studebaker Lark automobiles (1959-1966), Studebaker Gran Turismo Hawk automobiles (1962-1964) and Studebaker Champ trucks (1960-1964).
[src:dead-centre-engineering/air-filter] The filter was an aluminum frame containing an aluminum mesh and was located directly above the heater core.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/air-filter] The filter was removed and installed from the engine compartment through a slot in the firewall.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/air-filter] A long, thin rubber seal plugged the slot when the filter was installed.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/air-filter] The filter could be vacuumed and washed prior to installation.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/air-filter] Clogged or dirty cabin air filters can reduce airflow available to the cabin vents, as well as introduce allergens into the cabin air stream.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/air-filter] Since the cabin air temperature depends upon the flow rate of the air passing through the heater core, the evaporator, or both, clogged filters can greatly reduce the effectiveness and performance of the vehicle's air conditioning and heating systems.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/air-filter] At the point of retail to the consumer, cabin air filter suppliers do not share performance testing characteristics listed below.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/air-filter] However, some cabin air filter manufacturers do print a minimum efficiency reporting value (MERV) filter rating or cite N95 (however disclaim any NIOSH compliance) on their cabin air filter retail boxes.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/air-filter] Pleat spacing (inversely pleat count) of air filter media is inversely proportional to filtration efficiency.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/air-filter] Airflow and pressure drop of air filter media is inversely proportional to filtration efficiency.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/air-filter] The combustion air filter prevents abrasive particulate matter from entering the engine's cylinders, causing mechanical wear, oil contamination, and change to emissions performance.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/air-filter] Many modern fuel injected vehicles use a pleated paper filter element in the form of a flat panel, usually placed inside a plastic box connected to the throttle body with duct work.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/air-filter] The overall unit (filter and housing, and duct work together) is called the **air cleaner**.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/air-filter] Air intake filter media technology improvements have helped increase overall efficiency of gas turbine air-compressors by using simulation tools to optimize aerodynamics and fluid dynamics.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/air-filter] Pleated paper filter elements are the nearly exclusive choice for automobile engine air cleaners, because they are efficient, easy to service, and cost-effective.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/air-filter] The "paper" term is somewhat misleading, as the paper filter media is constructed differently from papers used for writing or packaging, by employing binding resins or surface modifications.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/air-filter] The paper is pleated/bent in a zig-zag shape to increase the filtration surface area of the paper encountered by the airflow path, in the range of 50 times that of the air opening.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/air-filter] There is a persistent belief among tuners, reinforced by advertising for aftermarket non-paper replacement filters manufacturers, that paper filters flow poorly enough to restrict engine performance.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/air-filter] However, as long as a pleated-paper filter is sized appropriately for the airflow volumes encountered in a particular application, such filters present only a trivial restriction to flow and pressure drop until the filter has become significantly clogged with dirt.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/air-filter] Oil-wetted polyurethane foam elements are used in some aftermarket replacement automobile air filters.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/air-filter] Foam was in the past widely used in air cleaners on small engines on lawnmowers and other power equipment, but automotive-type paper filter elements have largely supplanted oil-wetted foam in these applications.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/air-filter] Foam filters are still commonly used on air compressors for air tools up to 5 horsepower (3.7 kW).
[src:dead-centre-engineering/air-filter] Due to the way dust is captured on foam filters, large amounts may be trapped without measurable change in airflow restriction.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/air-filter] Oiled cotton gauze is employed in a growing number of aftermarket automotive air filters marketed as high-performance items.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/air-filter] In the 1970's, with the introduction of the Fiat Abarth SS versions, cotton gauze air filters as OE automotive engine filters gained market traction.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/air-filter] Metal Mesh (stainless steel for rust resistance) is another example of an air filter media which can be ordered with different mesh counts to adjust for desired performance characteristics.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/air-filter] In an extremely modified engine lacking the space for a cone-based air filter, some will opt to install a simple stainless steel mesh over the hot turbo to reduce certain particles sizes from entering the engine via the turbo.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/air-filter] An oil bath air cleaner consists of a sump containing a pool of oil and an insert which is filled with fiber, mesh, foam, or another coarse filter media.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/air-filter] The cleaner removes particles by adhering them to the oil-soaked filter media; as opposed to traditional filtration, the openings in the filter media are much larger than the particles that are to be filtered.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/air-filter] When the cleaner is assembled, the media-containing body of the insert sits a short distance above the surface of the oil pool.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/air-filter] The rim of the insert overlaps the rim of the sump.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/air-filter] This U-turn takes the air at high velocity across the surface of the oil pool.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/air-filter] Heavier (and typically larger) dust and dirt particles in the air cannot make the turn due to their inertia, so they fall into the oil and settle to the bottom of the base bowl.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/air-filter] Lighter (and typically smaller) particles stick to the filtration media in the insert, which is wetted by oil droplets aspirated there by normal airflow.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/air-filter] The constant aspiration of oil onto the filter media slowly carries most of the finer trapped particles downward and the oil drips back into the reservoir where the particles accumulate.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/air-filter] Oil bath air cleaners were very widely used in automotive and small engine applications until the widespread industry adoption of the paper filter in the early 1960s.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/air-filter] Such cleaners are still used in off-road equipment where very high levels of dust are encountered, for oil bath air cleaners can sequester a great deal of dirt relative to their overall size without loss of filtration efficiency or airflow.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/air-filter] In the early 20th century (about 1900 to 1930), water bath air cleaners were used in some applications (cars, trucks, tractors, and portable and stationary engines).
[src:dead-centre-engineering/air-filter] They worked on roughly the same principles as oil bath air cleaners.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/air-filter] For example, the original Fordson tractor had a water bath air cleaner.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/air-filter] By the 1940s, oil bath designs had displaced water bath designs because of better filtering performance.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/air-filter] Bulk solids handling involves the transport of solids (mechanical transport, pneumatic transport) which may be in a powder form.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/air-filter] Many industries are handling bulk solids (mining industries, chemical industries, food industries) which requires the treatment of air streams escaping the process so that fine particles are not emitted, for regulatory reasons or economical reasons (loss of materials).
[src:dead-centre-engineering/air-filter] As a consequence, air filters are positioned at many places in the process, especially at the reception of pneumatic conveying lines where the quantity of air is important and the load in fine particle quite important.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/air-filter] Filters can also be placed at any point of air exchange in the process to avoid that pollutants enter the process, which is particularly true in pharmaceuticals and food industries.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/air-filter] European standard EN 779, on which the above table is based, remained in effect from 2012 to mid-2018, when it was replaced by ISO 16890.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/airbox] An **airbox** is an empty chamber on the inlet of most combustion engines.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/airbox] It collects air from outside and feeds it to the intake hoses of each cylinder.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/airbox] Older engines drew air directly from the surroundings into each individual carburetor.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/airbox] Modern engines instead draw air into an airbox, which is connected by individual hoses to each carburetor or directly to the intake ports in fuel-injected engines, thus avoiding an extra intake manifold.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/airbox] The airbox allows the use of one air filter instead of multiples, reducing complexity.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/airbox] Developments arising from concerns about engine emissions during the late 1970s allow the airbox to collect pump gases from the crankcase and the tank air vent and re-feed them to the engine.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/airbox] Since the 1990s, engine designers also sought to exploit the properties of oscillating gas to improve performance.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/airbox] Many high-performance motorcycles have the airbox fed from funnels in the front of the bike, where increased pressure forces more air into the intake and thus improves power.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/airbox] Examples of this ram-air intake construction are the SRAD models of the Suzuki GSX-R750, the Kawasaki Ninja ZX-6R or the BMW S1000RR.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/airbox] Secondly, designers exploit a property of air cavities known as Helmholtz resonance.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/airbox] Flow through the airbox is optimal at its resonance frequency, which depends on airbox volume and the inlet area and length of the snorkel.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/airbox] The resonance is typically chosen to be at a medium speed where torque otherwise drops, caused by valve timing overlap.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine-controls] *Right* - The left magneto p-lead is grounded, and the right is open.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine-controls] This disables the left magneto and enables the right magneto only.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine-controls] *Left* - The right magneto p-lead is grounded, and the left is open.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine-controls] This disables the right magneto and enables the left magneto only.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine-controls] *Both* - This is the normal operating configuration, both p-leads are open, enabling both magnetos.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine-controls] *Start* - The pinion gear on the starter motor is engaged with the flywheel and the starter motor runs to turn the engine over.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine-controls] In most cases, only the left magneto is active (the right p-lead is grounded) due to timing differences between the magnetos at low RPMs.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine-controls] In an aircraft with a **fixed-pitch propeller**, there is no direct control over the propeller rotational speed, which depends on the airspeed and loading.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine-controls] Therefore, the pilot has to pay attention to the RPM indicator and adjust the throttle/power lever in order to maintain the desired constant speed of the propeller.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine-controls] For example, when the airspeed reduces and the loading increases (e.g., in a climb), RPM will decrease and the pilot has to increase the throttle/power.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine-controls] When the airspeed increases and the loading decreases (e.g., in a dive), the RPM will increase and the pilot has to decrease the throttle/power in order to prevent RPM from exceeding the operational limits and damaging the motor.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine-controls] Restricting the volume of cooling airflow too much.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine-controls] Insufficient delivery of lubricating oil to the engine's moving parts.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine-starting] Many variations of **aircraft engine starting** have been used since the Wright brothers made their first powered flight in 1903.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine-starting] The methods used have been designed for weight saving, simplicity of operation and reliability.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine-starting] Early piston engines were started by hand.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine-starting] Geared hand starting, electrical and cartridge-operated systems for larger engines were developed between the First and Second World Wars.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine-starting] Gas turbine aircraft engines such as turbojets, turboshafts and turbofans often use air/pneumatic starting, with the use of *bleed air* from built-in auxiliary power units (APUs) or external air compressors now seen as a common starting method.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine-starting] Often only one engine needs be started using the APU (or remote compressor).
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine-starting] After the first engine is started using APU bleed air, *cross-bleed air* from the running engine can be used to start the remaining engine(s).
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine-starting] Hand starting of aircraft piston engines by swinging the propeller is the oldest and simplest method, the absence of any onboard starting system giving an appreciable weight saving.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine-starting] Positioning of the propeller relative to the crankshaft is arranged such that the engine pistons pass through top dead centre during the swinging stroke.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine-starting] As the ignition system is normally arranged to produce sparks before top dead centre there is a risk of the engine kicking back during hand starting.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine-starting] To avoid this problem one of the two magnetos used in a typical aero engine ignition system is fitted with an 'impulse coupling', a spring-loaded device which delays the spark until top dead centre and which also increases the rotational speed of the magneto to produce a stronger spark.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine-starting] When the engine fires, the impulse coupling no longer operates and the second magneto is switched on.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine-starting] Note that this is different from the manual "turning over" of a radial piston engine, which is done to release oil that has become trapped in the lower cylinders prior to starting to avoid engine damage.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine-starting] The two appear similar, but while hand starting involves a sharp, strong "yank" on the prop to start the engine, turning over is simply done by turning the prop through a certain set amount.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine-starting] Accidents have occurred during lone pilot hand starting, whether due to high throttle settings, brakes not having been applied, or wheel chocks not being used, all resulting in the aircraft moving off without the pilot at the controls.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine-starting] The Hucks starter (invented by Bentfield Hucks during WWI) is a mechanical replacement for the ground crew.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine-starting] Based on a vehicle chassis the device uses a clutch driven shaft to turn the propeller, disengaging as the engine starts.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine-starting] A Hucks starter is used regularly at the Shuttleworth Collection for starting period aircraft.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine-starting] Self-sustaining motor gliders (often known as 'turbos') are fitted with small two-stroke engines with no starting system, for ground testing a cord is wrapped around the propeller boss and pulled rapidly in conjunction with operating decompressor valves.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine-starting] These engines are started in flight by operating the decompressor and increasing airspeed to windmill the propeller.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine-starting] Early variants of the Slingsby Falke motor glider use a cockpit mounted pull start system.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine-starting] Aircraft began to be equipped with electrical systems around 1930, powered by a battery and small wind-driven generator.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine-starting] The systems were initially not powerful enough to drive starter motors.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine-starting] Introduction of engine-driven generators solved the problem.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine-starting] Introduction of electric starter motors for aero engines increased convenience at the expense of extra weight and complexity.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine-starting] They were a necessity for flying boats with high mounted, inaccessible engines.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine-starting] Powered by an onboard battery, ground electrical supply or both, the starter is operated by a key or switch in the cockpit.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine-starting] The key system usually facilitates switching of the magnetos.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine-starting] In cold ambient conditions the friction caused by viscous engine oil causes a high load on the starting system.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine-starting] Another problem is the reluctance of the fuel to vaporise and combust at low temperatures.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine-starting] Oil dilution systems were developed (mixing fuel with the engine oil), and engine pre-heaters were used (including lighting fires under the engine).
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine-starting] The Ki-Gass priming pump system was used to assist starting of British engines.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine-starting] Aircraft fitted with variable-pitch propellers or constant speed propellers are started in fine pitch to reduce air loads and current in the starter motor circuit.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine-starting] Many light aircraft are fitted with a 'starter engaged' warning light in the cockpit, a mandatory airworthiness requirement to guard against the risk of the starter motor failing to disengage from the engine.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine-starting] The Coffman starter was an explosive cartridge operated device, the burning gases either operating directly in the cylinders to rotate the engine or operating through a geared drive.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine-starting] First introduced on the Junkers Jumo 205 diesel engine in 1936 the Coffman starter was not widely used by civil operators due to the expense of the cartridges.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine-starting] In 1920 Roy Fedden designed a piston engine gas starting system, used on the Bristol Jupiter engine in 1922.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine-starting] A system used in early Rolls-Royce Kestrel engines ducted high-pressure air from a ground unit through a camshaft driven distributor to the cylinders via non-return valves, the system had disadvantages only overcome by conversion to electric starting.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine-starting] When a piston engine needs to be started in flight the electric starter motor can be used.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine-starting] This is a normal procedure for motor gliders that have been soaring with the engine turned off.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine-starting] During aerobatics with earlier aircraft types it was not uncommon for the engine to cut during manoeuvres due to carburettor design.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine-starting] With no electric starter installed, engines can be restarted by diving the aircraft to increase airspeed and the rotation speed of the 'windmilling' propeller.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine-starting] An aero engine inertia starter uses a pre-rotated flywheel to transfer kinetic energy to the crankshaft, normally through reduction gears and a clutch to prevent over-torque conditions.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine-starting] Three variations have been used, hand driven, electrically driven and a combination of both.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine-starting] When the flywheel is fully energised either a manual cable is pulled or a solenoid is used to engage the starter.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine-starting] Starting of a gas turbine engine requires rotation of the compressor to a speed that provides sufficient pressurised air to the combustion chambers.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine-starting] The starting system has to overcome inertia of the compressor and friction loads, the system remains in operation after combustion starts and is disengaged once the engine has reached self-idling speed.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine-starting] Two types of electrical starter motor can be used, direct-cranking (to disengage as internal combustion engines) and starter-generator system (permanently engaged).
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine-starting] Small gas turbine engines, particularly turboshaft engines used in helicopters and cruise missile turbojets can be started by a geared hydraulic motor using oil pressure from a ground supply.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine-starting] With air-start systems, gas turbine engine compressor spools are rotated by the action of a large volume of compressed air acting directly on the compressor blades or driving the engine through a small, geared turbine motor.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine-starting] These motors can weigh up to 75% less than an equivalent electrical system.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine-starting] The compressed air can be supplied from an on-board auxiliary power unit (APU), a portable gas generator used by ground crew or by cross feeding bleed air from a running engine in the case of multi-engined aircraft.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine-starting] The Turbomeca Palouste gas generator was used to start the Spey engines of the Blackburn Buccaneer.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine-starting] The de Havilland Sea Vixen was equipped with its own Palouste in a removable underwing container to facilitate starting when away from base.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine-starting] Other military aircraft types using ground supplied compressed air for starting include the Lockheed F-104 Starfighter and variants of the F-4 Phantom using the General Electric J79 turbojet engine.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine-starting] Versions of the Rolls-Royce Avon turbojet engine used a geared turbine starter motor that burned isopropyl nitrate as the fuel.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine-starting] In military service this monofuel had the NATO designation of S-746 AVPIN.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine-starting] For starting a measured amount of fuel was introduced to the starter combustion chamber then ignited electrically, the hot gases spinning the turbine at high revolutions with the exhaust exiting overboard.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine-starting] Similar in operating principle to the piston engine Coffman starter, an explosive cartridge drives a small turbine engine which is connected by gears to the compressor shaft.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine-starting] Developed for short-haul airliners, most civil and military aircraft requiring self-contained starting systems these units are known by various names including Auxiliary Power Unit (APU), Jet Fuel Starter (JFS), Air Start Unit (ASU) or Gas Turbine Compressor (GTC).
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine-starting] Comprising a small gas turbine which is electrically started, these devices provide compressed bleed air for engine starting and often also provide electrical and hydraulic power for ground operations without the need to run the main engines.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine-starting] Two small petrol/oil mix tanks were fitted in the annular intake.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine-starting] The Lockheed SR-71 Blackbird used two Buick Nailheads as starter motors, which were mounted on an AG-330 Start Kart trolley, later with Chevrolet big-block 454-cubic-inch (7.44 L) V8 engines.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine-starting] Gas turbine engines can be shut down in flight, intentionally by the crew to save fuel or during a flight test or unintentionally due to fuel starvation or flameout after a compressor stall.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine-starting] Sufficient airspeed is used to 'windmill' the compressor then fuel and ignition are switched on, an on-board auxiliary power unit may be used at high altitudes where the air density is lower.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine-starting] During zoom climb operations of the Lockheed NF-104A the jet engine was shut down on climbing through 85,000 ft (26,000 m) and was started using the windmill method on descent through denser air.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine-starting] Pulse jet engines are uncommon aircraft powerplants.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine-starting] However, the Argus As 014 used to power the V-1 flying bomb and Fieseler Fi 103R Reichenberg was a notable exception.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine-starting] Once the engine started and the temperature rose to the minimum operating level, the external air hose and connectors were removed, and the resonant design of the tailpipe kept the pulse jet firing.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine-starting] Each cycle or pulse of the engine began with the shutters open; fuel was injected behind them and ignited, and the resulting expansion of gases forced the shutters closed.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine-starting] As the pressure in the engine dropped following combustion, the shutters reopened and the cycle was repeated, roughly 40 to 45 times per second.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine-starting] The electrical ignition system was used only to start the engine; heating of the tailpipe skin maintained combustion.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine] An **aircraft engine**, often referred to as an **aero engine**, is the power component of an aircraft propulsion system.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine] Aircraft using power components are referred to as **powered flight**.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine] Most aircraft engines are either piston engines or gas turbines, although a few have been rocket powered and in recent years many small UAVs have used electric motors.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine] The market for aircraft engines, especially jet engines, has very high barriers to entry.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine] Aircraft engines use highly advanced technology and materials, take around eight years and billions of dollars or euros to develop, and must pass exacting safety certifications by aviation safety authorities.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine] Consequently, entering the engine market is extremely capital- and time-intensive, which helps protect existing manufacturers from competition.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine] The last successful entry in the global market for jet engines was General Electric in the 1970s.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine] These barriers to entry make the market very lucrative for existing manufacturers.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine] As of 2025, the leading jet engine manufacturers reported shareholder returns from between 100 and 1,000 percent over the last five years, compared to small or negative returns for their principal clients, Airbus and Boeing.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine] The engines themselves are typically sold at a loss, but manufacturers derive their profits from the sale of maintenance services and spare parts over the roughly thirty-year lifespan of an engine, following the razor and blades business model.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine] This creates a perverse incentive for manufacturers to slow the production or delay the delivery of new engines, because they profit most from the use of old engines, which need more service and spare parts than new ones.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine] This contributed to the unavailability of new engines, creating a bottleneck for Airbus and Boeing's efforts to increase aircraft production in the post-COVID resurgence of aviation after 2023.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine] A radial engine has the cylinders placed in a circle around the crankshaft.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine] The engine is air-cooled, which can be a problem since they may overheat.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine] Compared to liquid-cooled engines, radial engines have the advantage of being more rugged and capable of absorbing damage.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine] Rotating radial engines have the cylinders in a circle around the crankcase, as in a radial engine, (see above), but the crankshaft is fixed to the airframe and the propeller is fixed to the engine case, so that the crankcase and cylinders rotate.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine] The advantage of this arrangement is that a satisfactory flow of cooling air is maintained even at low airspeeds, retaining the weight advantage and simplicity of a conventional air-cooled engine without one of their major drawbacks.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine] The first practical rotary engine was the Gnome Omega designed by the Seguin brothers and first flown in 1909.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine] Its relative reliability and good power to weight ratio changed aviation dramatically.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine] The Wankel engine is about one half the weight and size of a traditional four-stroke cycle piston engine of equal power output, and much lower in complexity.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine] In an aircraft application, the power-to-weight ratio is very important, making the Wankel engine a good choice.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine] Because the engine is typically constructed with an aluminium housing and a steel rotor, and aluminium expands more than steel when heated, a Wankel engine does not seize when overheated, unlike a piston engine.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine] This is an important safety factor for aeronautical use.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine] Considerable development of these designs started after World War II, but at the time the aircraft industry favored the use of turbine engines.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine] It was believed that turbojet or turboprop engines could power all aircraft, from the largest to smallest designs.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine] The Wankel engine did not find many applications in aircraft, but was used by Mazda in a popular line of sports cars.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine] The French company Citroën had developed Wankel powered RE-2 helicopter in 1970's.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine] In modern times the Wankel engine has been used in motor gliders where the compactness, light weight, and smoothness are crucially important.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine] Starting in the 1930s, attempts were made to produce a practical aircraft diesel engine.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine] In general, Diesel engines are more reliable and much better suited to running for long periods of time at medium power settings.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine] Improvements in Diesel technology in automobiles (leading to much better power-weight ratios), the Diesel's much better fuel efficiency, and the high relative taxation of AVGAS compared to Jet A1 in Europe have all seen a revival of interest in the use of diesels for aircraft.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine] Thielert Aircraft Engines converted Mercedes Diesel automotive engines, certified them for aircraft use, and became an OEM provider to Diamond Aviation for their light twin.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine] Financial problems have plagued Thielert, so Diamond's affiliate — Austro Engine — developed the new AE300 turbodiesel, also based on a Mercedes engine.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine] A turboprop consists of an intake, reduction gearbox, compressor, combustor, turbine, and a propelling nozzle.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine] Air enters the intake and is compressed by the compressor.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine] Jet fuel is then added to the compressed air in the combustor, where it then combusts.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine] The hot combustion gases expand through the turbine stages, generating power at the point of exhaust.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine] Some of the power generated by the turbine is used to drive the compressor and electric generator.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine] The gases are then exhausted from the turbine, but do not provide enough power to create a major portion of the total thrust, since almost all of the engine's power is used to drive the propeller.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine] A **turboshaft** engine is a form of gas turbine that is optimized to produce shaft horsepower rather than jet thrust.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine] The engine has two major parts assemblies: the 'gas generator' and the 'power section'.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine] The gas generator consists of the compressor, combustion chambers with ignitors and fuel nozzles, and one or more stages of turbine.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine] The power section consists of additional stages of turbines, a gear reduction system, and the shaft output.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine] The gas generator creates the hot expanding gases to drive the power section; the engine accessories may be driven either by the gas generator or by the power section.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine] A number of electrically powered aircraft, such as the QinetiQ Zephyr, have been designed since the 1960s.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine] In France in late 2007, a conventional light aircraft powered by an 18 kW electric motor using lithium polymer batteries was flown, covering more than 50 kilometers (31 mi), the first electric airplane to receive a certificate of airworthiness.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine] On 18 May 2020, the Pipistrel E-811 was the first electric aircraft engine to be awarded a type certificate by EASA for use in general aviation.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine] The E-811 powers the Pipistrel Velis Electro.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine] Many big companies, such as Siemens, are developing high-performance electric engines for aircraft use; also, SAE shows new developments in elements as pure Copper core electric motors with a better efficiency.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine] A hybrid system as emergency back-up and for added power in take-off is offered for sale by Axter Aerospace, Madrid, Spain.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine] The term *advanced technology engine* refers to the modern generation of jet engines.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine] A rocket turbine engine is a combination of two types of propulsion engines: a liquid-propellant rocket and a turbine jet engine.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine] Its power-to-weight ratio is a little higher than a regular jet engine, and it works at higher altitudes.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine] At the April 2018 ILA Berlin Air Show, Munich-based research institute de:Bauhaus Luftfahrt presented a high-efficiency composite cycle engine for 2050, combining a geared turbofan with a piston engine core.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine] The 11,200 lb (49.7 kN) engine could power a 50-seat regional jet.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine] Its cruise TSFC would be 11.5 g/kN/s (0.406 lb/lbf/hr) for an overall engine efficiency of 48.2%, for a burner temperature of 1,700 K (1,430 °C), an overall pressure ratio of 38 and a peak pressure of 30 MPa (300 bar).
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine] Although engine weight increases by 30%, aircraft fuel consumption is reduced by 15%.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine] Sponsored by the European Commission under Framework 7 project LEMCOTEC, Bauhaus Luftfahrt, MTU Aero Engines and GKN Aerospace presented the concept in 2015, raising the overall engine pressure ratio to over 100 for a 15.2% fuel burn reduction compared to 2025 engines.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine] On multi-engine aircraft, engine positions are numbered from left to right from the point of view of the pilot looking forward, so for example on a four-engine aircraft such as the Boeing 747, engine No.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine] 1 is on the left side, farthest from the fuselage, while engine No.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine] 3 is on the right side nearest to the fuselage.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine] In the case of the twin-engine English Electric Lightning, which has two fuselage-mounted jet engines one above the other, engine No.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine] 1 is below and to the front of engine No.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine] Refineries blend Avgas with tetraethyllead (TEL) to achieve these high octane ratings, a practice that governments no longer permit for gasoline intended for road vehicles.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine] The shrinking supply of TEL and the possibility of environmental legislation banning its use have made a search for replacement fuels for general aviation aircraft a priority for pilots’ organizations.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine] Model aircraft typically use nitro engines (also known as "glow engines" due to the use of a glow plug) powered by glow fuel, a mixture of methanol, nitromethane, and lubricant.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine] Electrically powered model airplanes and helicopters are also commercially available.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/aircraft-engine] Small multicopter UAVs are almost always powered by electricity, but larger gasoline-powered designs are under development.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/dead-centre-engineering] In a reciprocating engine, the **dead centre** is the position of a piston in which it is either furthest from, or nearest to, the crankshaft.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/dead-centre-engineering] The former is known as **top dead centre** (**TDC**) while the latter is known as **bottom dead centre** (**BDC**).
[src:dead-centre-engineering/dead-centre-engineering] More generally, the dead centre is any position of a crank where the applied force is straight along its axis, meaning no turning force can be applied.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/dead-centre-engineering] Many sorts of machines are crank driven, including unicycles, bicycles, tricycles, various types of machine presses, gasoline engines, diesel engines, steam locomotives, and other steam engines.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/dead-centre-engineering] Crank-driven machines rely on the energy stored in a flywheel to overcome the dead centre, or are designed, in the case of multi-cylinder engines, so that dead centres can never exist on all cranks at the same time.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/dead-centre-engineering] A steam locomotive is an example of the latter, the connecting rods being arranged such that the dead centre for each cylinder occurs out of phase with the other one (or more) cylinders.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/dead-centre-engineering] Bicycle cranks have dead centres at approximately 12 o'clock and 6 o'clock where simple pushing down of the pedal will not turn the chainwheel, but the rider's leg can apply tangential force at the pedal to overcome it.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/dead-centre-engineering] Fixed-gear bicycles (without a freehub) use the momentum of the bicycle and rider to keep the chainwheel turning even if the rider makes no attempt to pedal in a circular motion.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/dead-centre-engineering] In a reciprocating engine, top dead centre of piston #1 is the point from which ignition system measurements are made and the firing order is determined.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/dead-centre-engineering] For example, ignition timing is normally specified as degrees of crankshaft rotation **before top dead centre** (**BTDC**).
[src:dead-centre-engineering/dead-centre-engineering] A very few small and fast-burning engines require a spark just **after top dead centre** (**ATDC**), such as the Nissan MA engine with hemispherical combustions, or hydrogen engines.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/dead-centre-engineering] Top dead centre for cylinder one is often marked on the crankshaft pulley, the flywheel or harmonic balancer or both, with adjacent timing marks showing the recommended ignition timing settings as decided during engine development.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/dead-centre-engineering] The timing marks can be used to set the ignition timing either statically by hand or dynamically using a timing light, by rotating the distributor in its seat.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/dead-centre-engineering] In a multi-cylinder engine, pistons may reach top dead centre simultaneously or at different times depending on the engine configuration.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/dead-centre-engineering] The concept of top dead centre is also extended to pistonless rotary engines, and means the point in the cycle in which the volume of a combustion chamber is smallest.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/dead-centre-engineering] This typically occurs several times per rotor revolution.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/dead-centre-engineering] In the Wankel engine for example, it occurs three times for every one revolution of the rotor (although only once per revolution of the engine output shaft, since the output rotates at three times the speed of the rotor).
[src:dead-centre-engineering/dead-centre-engineering] Finding the volume of the cylinder using TDC and BDC and multiplying it by the number of cylinders will give the engine displacement.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/dead-centre-engineering] As steam engines are commonly horizontal, the relevant terms are front dead centre and back dead centre rather than "top" and "bottom".
[src:dead-centre-engineering/dead-centre-engineering] If a single-cylinder steam engine stops in either of the dead centre positions, it must be moved off the dead centre before it will restart.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/dead-centre-engineering] In small engines, this is done by turning the flywheel by hand.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/dead-centre-engineering] In large engines, the flywheel is moved with a lever or "turning bar".
[src:dead-centre-engineering/dead-centre-engineering] Both operations must be done with care to avoid the operator becoming entangled in the machinery.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/dead-centre-engineering] Even larger engines might require the use of a barring engine.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/dead-centre-engineering] Steam locomotives normally have at least two double acting cylinders, which enables the cranks to be set so that at least one piston will always be off the dead centre and no starting assistance is required.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/dead-centre-engineering] In the common case of a two piston locomotive, the cranks are set at right angles, so that whenever one piston is at dead centre the other is in mid-stroke, and giving four equally spaced power strokes per revolution.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/dead-centre-engineering] This term is also used in the realm of production equipment.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/dead-centre-engineering] A mechanical punch press employs a crankshaft similar to that found in an engine.
[src:dead-centre-engineering/dead-centre-engineering] In the punch press, the crankshaft drives a ram that when it is furthest away from the platen of the press is deemed to be in the position of top dead centre.
